03930nmm a2200613Ia 9780801465802DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20122014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014658027 a10.7591/97808014658022doi  a(DE-B1597)496389  a(OCoLC)1041991368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aR735b.Q47 201304a610.722304aThe Question of Competence :bReconsidering Medical Education in the Twenty-First Century /ced. by Lorelei Lingard, Brian D. Hodges. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMedical competence is a hot topic surrounded by much controversy about how to define competency, how to teach it, and how to measure it. While some debate the pros and cons of competence-based medical education and others explain how to achieve various competencies, the authors of the seven chapters in The Question of Competence offer something very different. They critique the very notion of competence itself and attend to how it has shaped what we pay attention to—and what we ignore—in the education and assessment of medical trainees. Two leading figures in the field of medical education, Brian D. Hodges and Lorelei Lingard, drew together colleagues from the United States, Canada, and the Netherlands to explore competency from different perspectives, in order to spark thoughtful discussion and debate on the subject. The critical analyses included in the book’s chapters cover the role of emotion, the implications of teamwork, interprofessional frameworks, the construction of expertise, new directions for assessment, models of self-regulation, and the concept of mindful practice. The authors juxtapose the idea of competence with other highly valued ideas in medical education such as emotion, cognition and teamwork, drawing new insights about their intersections and implications for one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aClinical competence. 0aCompetency-based education. 0aMedical education. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aMedicine & Medical Issues.  amedical competence, competency defined, medical assessment, medical controversy, education of medical trainees, critique of competency.1 aAnderson, M. Brownell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodges, Brian D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLingard, Lorelei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146580240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465802/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles